# {{CAMPAIGN_NAME}}

A TTRPG campaign repo, scaffolded by the `ttrpg-gm` plugin.

## Campaign metadata

- **Name:** {{CAMPAIGN_NAME}}
- **System:** {{CAMPAIGN_SYSTEM}}

## What lives here

This repo is the GM-owned home for one campaign. The GM is the user of this system; PCs are the player characters at the table; NPCs are any character voiced by the GM. The campaign holds one party, one ongoing run of sessions, and one campaign-local truth about the world.

For the current state of the campaign at a glance (active adventures, open threads, recent consequences, party location), see [`campaign.md`](./campaign.md). That file is agent-maintained — regenerated by `/wrap-session` and by `/ingest`. Don't hand-edit it as a primary workflow; the next regeneration will reconcile or overwrite.

## Available slash commands

These commands ship with the `ttrpg-gm` plugin and operate against this repo:

- **`/ingest`** — extract structure from existing campaign notes (markdown files) into this scaffolded repo. Surveys docs, processes them per-doc with GM approval, and regenerates `campaign.md` at the end.
- **`/prep-session`** — create a new session directory (`sessions/YYYY-MM-DD-session-N/`) and seed a structured `brief.md` from the campaign's current state. GM-editable before play.
- **`/wrap-session`** — read the session's `notes.md`, draft a `log.md`, propose new Threads, Consequences, Reference notes, Beat deliveries, and Adventure status changes for GM approval, and regenerate `campaign.md`.

## Lifecycle objects (overview)

The campaign is organized around a small set of file kinds, each in its own directory. One file per item — `[[wiki links]]` and backlinks do the connective work.

**Reference notes** — static, linked-to entries about things in the world. One file per item.

- `pcs/` — player characters at the table. One file per PC.
- `npcs/` — non-player characters voiced by the GM (recurring or one-off).
- `locations/` — places.
- `factions/` — groups, organizations, courts.
- `items/` — objects that matter narratively or mechanically.

**Containers**

- `adventures/<name>/` — story arcs the party runs inside the campaign. Each is its own directory with frontmatter for status, order, dates, and durations. See `.claude/rules/adventures.md` for the schema and status transitions.
- `sessions/YYYY-MM-DD-session-N/` — one directory per session, containing `brief.md`, `notes.md`, and `log.md`. Three documents, three lifecycles. See `.claude/rules/sessions.md`.

**Lifecycle objects** — first-class files with status, created mostly via post-session extraction.

- `threads/` — open hooks, promises, foreshadowed dangers. Future-facing. Status: `open`, `closed`, `decayed`.
- `consequences/` — persistent facts about the world resulting from the party's actions. Past-facing; persists, doesn't close.
- `beats/` — GM-authored intentions to deliver a specific moment opportunistically. Future-facing. Status: `pending`, `delivered`, `dropped`. Optional `kind:` discriminator (`news | handout | character-moment | set-piece | clue | escalation`).
- `secrets/` — facts about the world the party might not know yet but could learn. Status: `hidden`, `partially-revealed`, `revealed`. Each Secret's `belongs_to:` lists the non-ephemeral containers (Adventures / NPCs / PCs / Locations / Factions / Items) it belongs to; those containers carry a back-reference `## Secrets` section that the agent maintains symmetrically.

**Campaign overview**

- `campaign.md` — agent-maintained snapshot of current campaign state. Regenerated by `/wrap-session` and `/ingest`.

## Linking syntax

This campaign uses **`[[wiki link]]` syntax** for cross-references. Examples:

- `[[Sera]]` — link to `npcs/sera.md` (or wherever a file named `Sera` lives).
- `[[Curse of Strahd]]` — link to the `adventures/curse-of-strahd/` adventure.
- `[[the iron key]]` — link to `items/the-iron-key.md`.

Resolution is by filename match (case-insensitive, with light normalization). Backlinks tell the agent which files reference a given item — used to scope Beats to adventures, surface NPC appearances, and answer "what's the last thing the party did involving X?".

Do not invent alternative link syntaxes. `[[wiki link]]` is the convention.

## Writing style and voice

This campaign carries a GM-authored writing-style guide at [`.claude/rules/style.md`](./.claude/rules/style.md). It steers the prose voice of any artifact the agent drafts under `sessions/`, `adventures/`, `npcs/`, `pcs/`, `locations/`, `factions/`, `items/`, `threads/`, `consequences/`, `beats/`, `secrets/`, and `.ttrpg-staging/` — Briefs, Logs, Reference-note bodies, Adventure descriptions, lifecycle-object prose.

**Agents working in this directory**: before drafting any prose body for files under the directories above, Read `.claude/rules/style.md` if it exists and apply its constraints throughout the drafting session. One Read early covers all subsequent drafting; re-Read if compaction may have dropped the content. (Claude Code's path-scoped auto-load is unreliable on the Write tool — [#23478](https://github.com/anthropics/claude-code/issues/23478) — so explicit Read is the durable mechanism.)

The file is **GM-authored, not agent-written**. The scaffolder ships a stub with placeholder sections (formality, tense, vocabulary, PC referencing, narrative voice); fill in the sections that matter, leave or delete the rest. Keep it tight — roughly 50 to 200 lines, prose with examples rather than rule lists.

